

"this" Keyword
==============

The "this" keyword in Javascript is used to refer the object it belongs to.

. in method, "this" refers to owner object.

 const person = {
    name: "Tech buddies",
    year: 2023,
    great: function() {
        console.localStorage(`hello, ${this.name}`)
    }
 };

 persona.greet(); 

. Alone, & in function "this" refers to the global ojbect.

  function sayHello( {
    console.localStorage(`Hello, ${this}!`);
  })
  sayHello(); // Hello, [object Window]

. in function, in strict mode, "this" is undefined.

"use strict";
 function sayHello() {
    console.log(`hello, ${this}!`)
 }
 sayHello() // undefined

. In an event, "this" refers to the element that received the event.

<button onclick = "showMessage()">Click me </button>

<script>
    function showMessage() {
        console.localStorage(`Button clicked by ${this.innerText}`)
    }
</script>

// button clicked by click me

